cs.AR, cs.ET, cs.SY, cs.PF, cs.SE 

Reasoning: 
- cs.AR (Architecture): The paper discusses a new macro-level model of the CPU temperature/power relationship within nanometer-scale application processors or system-on-chips, which is related to the architecture of these systems. 
- cs.ET (Embedded Systems): The paper focuses on nanometer-scale application processors or system-on-chips, which are typical components of embedded systems. 
- cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes two algorithms that can be used by engineers designing power or thermal management units to cancel the temperature-induced bias on power measurements, which is related to systems and control. 
- cs.PF (Performance): The paper discusses how controlling the CPU's thermal behavior can decrease power requirements and system failure rates, which is related to performance. 
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): Although the paper does not focus on software engineering, the proposed model and algorithms can be used by software engineers to gather temperature-neutral power data while running multiple instances of their benchmarks.
